# PID Control Theory

PID (Proportional-Integral-Derivative) control is a closed-loop control technique used to regulate system response based on feedback error.

The controller continuously compares the desired setpoint with the measured output from the encoder and calculates a correction signal.

## Proportional Term (P)

The proportional term reacts to the present error.

A larger error produces a stronger correction response.

## Integral Term (I)

The integral term accumulates past error over time.

It helps reduce steady-state error and improves long-term accuracy.

## Derivative Term (D)

The derivative term predicts future error trends by analyzing the rate of error change.

It improves damping and reduces oscillations.

